for some reason.

665
00:50:25,293 --> 00:50:29,002
- Cindy, I wanted to tell you...
- No, Miles.

666
00:50:29,053 --> 00:50:33,012
I heard about you and Janine. I'm so sorry.

667
00:50:34,693 --> 00:50:37,082
You never loved her, Miles.

668
00:50:37,133 --> 00:50:39,169
You know you didn't.

669
00:50:41,213 --> 00:50:43,204
That's what she says, oddly enough.

670
00:50:45,213 --> 00:50:51,209
I lied, Miles. I'm not sorry. Your divorce
gives me a slender thread of hope.

671
00:50:52,853 --> 00:50:54,969
I still love you, Miles.

672
00:50:55,013 --> 00:50:57,129
I know you wish I didn't,

673
00:50:57,173 --> 00:50:59,562
but I can't help it.

674
00:50:59,613 --> 00:51:02,411
It's the one thing the lithium can't touch.

675
00:51:03,133 --> 00:51:06,921
It washes into your brain
and it makes things easier, but...

676
00:51:08,453 --> 00:51:11,047
it can't erase what's here.

677
00:51:12,853 --> 00:51:15,572
It can't change what's here,

678
00:51:15,613 --> 00:51:17,604
what's in a woman's heart.

679
00:51:20,493 --> 00:51:22,290
Cindy.

680
00:51:23,933 --> 00:51:25,525
Cindy.

681
00:51:29,173 --> 00:51:30,970
Please.

682
00:51:39,253 --> 00:51:40,971
- Careful
- Yeah, you go.

683
00:51:41,013 --> 00:51:42,810
- You OK?
- Yeah.

684
00:51:42,853 --> 00:51:44,844
You're sure, now?

685
00:51:50,133 --> 00:51:51,407
Damn!

686
00:51:52,173 --> 00:51:54,323
Timmy, you are such a little pill.

687
00:52:02,053 --> 00:52:03,850
Sorry, Miles.

688
00:52:06,933 --> 00:52:11,484
<i>His little girl's accident</i>
<i>changed everything for CB Whiting.</i>

689
00:52:11,533 --> 00:52:15,685
<i>In a heartbeat. he went from thinking</i>
<i>of himself as someone special</i>

690
00:52:15,733 --> 00:52:19,089
<i>to someone especially damned.</i>

691
00:52:19,133 --> 00:52:23,126
<i>Was it seeing Cindy's limbs become</i>
<i>more twisted with each passing year</i>

692
00:52:23,173 --> 00:52:26,563
<i>that caused his 10-year-long meander</i>
<i>in Mexico?</i>

693
00:52:27,613 --> 00:52:33,370
<i>Was it her continued suffering that finally</i>
<i>lured him back to his own headwaters?</i>

694
00:52:34,413 --> 00:52:38,850
<i>Or was it some darker, selfish impulse?</i>

695
00:52:41,213 --> 00:52:43,090
<i>But that's in a later chapter.</i>

696
00:52:47,853 --> 00:52:52,051
Hello, dear boy. Did you like my surprise?

697
00:52:53,693 --> 00:52:55,684
Would you like some iced tea?

698
00:52:57,853 --> 00:52:59,923
Thank you.

699
00:52:59,973 --> 00:53:03,170
I see you've had another encounter
with Timmy.

700
00:53:04,253 --> 00:53:07,370
It's odd how she hates you so much.

701
00:53:07,413 --> 00:53:09,881
Of course, that little beast detests everyone,

702
00:53:09,933 --> 00:53:13,130
but you she seems to hold
in particular contempt.

703
00:53:13,173 --> 00:53:16,370
You should hold a raffle. 10 bucks a chance.

704
00:53:16,413 --> 00:53:19,689
The winner gets to beat her to death
with a baseball bat.

705
00:53:19,733 --> 00:53:23,089
You could fund a new wing of the hospital.

706
00:53:23,133 --> 00:53:26,125
Why is it I always forget
you have a sense of humour?

707
00:53:26,173 --> 00:53:29,961
- Did I say something funny?
- You didn't get it from your mother.

708
00:53:30,013 --> 00:53:36,725
She was a sweet woman, but she was not
blessed with a sense of life's grand folly.

709
00:53:36,773 --> 00:53:41,244
Actually, you know, my mother loved to laugh.

710
00:53:41,293 --> 00:53:46,321
- It's harder when you're the butt of the joke.
- Yes, well.

711
00:53:46,373 --> 00:53:49,649
Well, she did have a hard life.

712
00:53:49,693 --> 00:53:53,572
However, I've always felt
that people make their own luck.

713
00:53:55,093 --> 00:54:00,850
You needn't smile that smile, Miles Roby.
I know you think I married my luck.

714
00:54:00,893 --> 00:54:04,090
But that opinion is unkind

715
00:54:04,133 --> 00:54:06,124
and it does you no credit.

716
00:54:06,173 --> 00:54:10,132
There is a world of skill
in marrying the right person.

717
00:54:10,173 --> 00:54:12,641
And most people make a complete hash of it.

718
00:54:13,373 --> 00:54:18,401
I wager you have no idea any longer
of why you married.

719
00:54:18,453 --> 00:54:21,445
You'd wager
if you could find somebody to wager with.

720
00:54:21,493 --> 00:54:25,008
You married Janine
in order to escape an even worse fate.

721
00:54:26,373 --> 00:54:29,126
Could we discuss the restaurant?

722
00:54:29,173 --> 00:54:33,724
Yes, we can discuss whatever you like
or not discuss whatever you like.

723
00:54:34,373 --> 00:54:36,648
It's a lovely afternoon.

724
00:54:38,853 --> 00:54:42,528
- If I'm to continue running the Empire...
- Continue?

725
00:54:42,573 --> 00:54:45,770
Of course, you're going to continue.
That was our agreement.

726
00:54:45,813 --> 00:54:50,125
I've been running it faithfully
for over 25 years, Mrs Whiting,

727
00:54:50,173 --> 00:54:54,166
and I may be a slow learner,
but I have learned this much.

728
00:54:55,653 --> 00:54:58,008
There's no money in food.

729
00:54:58,053 --> 00:55:01,443
You know what's troubling you, dear boy?
It's not the restaurant.

730
00:55:01,493 --> 00:55:05,247
Here you are, about to be a bachelor again,

731
00:55:05,293 --> 00:55:09,002
and my daughter has returned to Empire Falls.

732
00:55:10,213 --> 00:55:13,410
My brother's weekend menus are a hit.

733
00:55:13,453 --> 00:55:15,808
Friday, Mexican. Saturday, Thai.

734
00:55:16,853 --> 00:55:18,650
If we could sell beer and wine...

735
00:55:21,373 --> 00:55:26,891
If your mother had had her way, you might've
found yourself at the altar with my daughter

736
00:55:26,933 --> 00:55:28,924
if you hadn't married when you did.

737
00:55:28,973 --> 00:55:31,692
I thought we were discussing
the state of the Grill.

738
00:55:31,733 --> 00:55:37,126
Frankly, I'm curious to see how
you manage things the second time around.

739
00:55:37,173 --> 00:55:38,526
Curious?

740
00:55:38,573 --> 00:55:43,408
Oh, please,
spare me that tone of moral superiority.

741
00:55:43,453 --> 00:55:47,924
That you do get from your mother.
It was her one tiresome trait.

742
00:55:51,653 --> 00:55:56,522
And what you really hate is the fact that
I know you better than you know yourself.

743
00:55:58,133 --> 00:55:59,930
Maybe I'll surprise you someday.

744
00:55:59,973 --> 00:56:03,204
Well, possibly. But you haven't yet.

745
00:56:04,773 --> 00:56:06,764
Incidentally...

746
00:56:07,733 --> 00:56:09,724
did my daughter let on to you

747
00:56:09,773 --> 00:56:13,163
that her doctors now believe that she's well?

748
00:56:15,573 --> 00:56:16,801
Yeah.

749
00:56:25,493 --> 00:56:27,085
Miles!

750
00:56:32,253 --> 00:56:35,290
Before, when I was trying to answer the door

751
00:56:35,333 --> 00:56:37,528
and you saw it was me,

752
00:56:37,573 --> 00:56:39,962
for a moment,

753
00:56:40,013 --> 00:56:43,085
it looked like you wanted to run away.

754
00:56:43,973 --> 00:56:49,525
No. It was a surprise, that's all.
A wonderful surprise.

755
00:56:51,093 --> 00:56:56,167
I can bear it that you don't love me, Miles.
I've borne it all my life.

756
00:56:56,213 --> 00:56:59,285
But if I thought I made you want to run away...

757
00:57:04,693 --> 00:57:07,127
Have you got plans for homecoming?

758
00:57:08,853 --> 00:57:12,402
Empire Falls and Fairhaven,
weekend after next?

759
00:57:13,973 --> 00:57:15,770
You're inviting me to homecoming?

760
00:57:17,333 --> 00:57:19,369
Yeah, why not?

761
00:57:22,373 --> 00:57:24,364
Oh, Miles!

762
00:57:26,573 --> 00:57:28,529
Dear, dear Miles.

763
00:57:31,253 --> 00:57:32,845
OK?

764
00:57:34,093 --> 00:57:36,084
- I'll call you.
- OK.

765
00:57:50,333 --> 00:57:52,130
Come here!

766
00:58:04,133 --> 00:58:06,124
You gotta be kidding me.

767
00:58:20,813 --> 00:58:23,611
<i>Your mother, she was a sweet woman,</i>

768
00:58:23,653 --> 00:58:28,408
<i>but she was not blessed</i>
<i>with a sense of life's grand folly.</i>

769
00:58:31,093 --> 00:58:35,371
Miles, look, we're coming up on the island.
Isn't it exciting?

770
00:58:38,653 --> 00:58:42,726
You know, there'll be lots more
Little League games when you get back.

771
00:58:43,253 --> 00:58:45,608
<i>And maybe we'll meet somebody nice.</i>

772
00:58:46,453 --> 00:58:50,162
- When's Dad coming?
- Maybe later in the week.

773
00:58:55,813 --> 00:58:57,804
Let's try to have fun, OK?

774
00:58:59,093 --> 00:59:01,084
Can we go to the beach?

775
00:59:01,133 --> 00:59:04,125
How about first thing? Yeah?

776
00:59:59,013 --> 01:00:01,004
Mom, your lobster.

777
01:00:01,053 --> 01:00:04,045
- Look at my steamers.
- That looks nice.

778
01:00:34,293 --> 01:00:35,885
Pretty good.

779
01:01:05,373 --> 01:01:07,967
- Who's that?
- Who's who?

780
01:01:18,973 --> 01:01:22,443
I thought you said the dining room
was too expensive.

781
01:01:22,493 --> 01:01:27,362
- I think we can afford to splurge one night.
- Will they have steamers?

782
01:01:28,613 --> 01:01:30,729
How do I look?

783
01:01:47,013 --> 01:01:49,004
What? I don't see them.

784
01:01:50,333 --> 01:01:55,168
I know. There's no steamers.
You have to order something else.

785
01:01:55,213 --> 01:01:57,408
Clams Casino.

786
01:01:59,093 --> 01:02:01,084
Yeah, Clams Casino.

787
01:02:02,173 --> 01:02:03,970
May I take your order?

788
01:02:04,013 --> 01:02:06,607
Clams Casino.

789
01:02:06,653 --> 01:02:09,645
Don't worry, if he doesn't like them, I do.

790
01:02:10,733 --> 01:02:13,042
I'll have the lobster.

791
01:02:13,093 --> 01:02:14,685
Thanks.

792
01:02:16,533 --> 01:02:19,969
- Pardon me, but are you eating alone?
- Alas!

793
01:02:21,253 --> 01:02:23,050
Would you like to join us?

794
01:02:23,093 --> 01:02:25,482
I seem to have the larger table.

795
01:02:26,333 --> 01:02:28,324
OK. Come on.

796
01:02:31,133 --> 01:02:34,443
- I haven't introduced myself. Charlie Mayne.
- We're from Maine.

797
01:02:34,493 --> 01:02:36,404
Really?

798
01:02:36,453 --> 01:02:38,364
Well, now, that's interesting.

799
01:02:38,413 --> 01:02:42,201
M-A-Y-N-E is how I spell my name.
How do you spell your state?

800
01:02:42,253 --> 01:02:43,925
The real way.

801
01:02:47,213 --> 01:02:49,932
- And I'm Grace.
- Yes.

802
01:02:51,653 --> 01:02:53,803
Yes, you are.

803
01:03:00,133 --> 01:03:06,288
I think somebody needs to thank Charlie
for a wonderful and very expensive dinner.

804
01:03:06,333 --> 01:03:10,042
Five orders of Clams Casino.
I bet that's a record.

805
01:03:13,213 --> 01:03:15,329
You know what?

806
01:03:15,373 --> 01:03:18,331
If we hurry, I think there's just time.

807
01:03:28,173 --> 01:03:30,562
Charlie, slow down!

808
01:03:30,613 --> 01:03:33,923
Faster! Faster!

809
01:03:54,453 --> 01:03:56,842
Oh, Charlie, look!

810
01:03:56,893 --> 01:03:58,884
What? Where?

811
01:04:03,253 --> 01:04:06,290
- Can I go walk on the beach?
- Sure.

812
01:04:14,693 --> 01:04:17,287
Take off your shoes, OK?
Don't get your pants wet.

813
01:04:17,333 --> 01:04:18,732
OK.

814
01:04:20,213 --> 01:04:22,010
Thank you.

815
01:04:31,773 --> 01:04:34,162
- What are you trying to catch?
- Fish.

816
01:04:34,213 --> 01:04:36,044
Big ones.

817
01:04:59,213 --> 01:05:02,250
- Something wrong?
- No.

818
01:05:02,293 --> 01:05:05,091
Except how come every time I look up,
I see you?

819
01:05:06,573 --> 01:05:09,770
- Small town, Miles.
- It's not that small.

820
01:05:11,533 --> 01:05:14,127
Maybe. Maybe not.

821
01:05:38,897 --> 01:05:42,492
- Those napkins cost money, you know.
- I'll pay you for 'em.

822
01:05:43,297 --> 01:05:45,765
I want my new name to be second nature.

823
01:05:45,817 --> 01:05:49,810
Goodbye, Janine Roby.
Hello, Janine Comeau.

824
01:05:50,897 --> 01:05:55,687
Did it ever occur to you
that I could use a hand with these boxes?

825
01:05:55,737 --> 01:05:59,525
After all these years,
you finally decided you don't like mule work?

826
01:05:59,577 --> 01:06:02,535
Give it up, Beatrice.
I'm not coming back to work for you.

827
01:06:02,577 --> 01:06:07,412
I got a job at one of the few successful
businesses in this whole sorry town.

828
01:06:07,457 --> 01:06:09,493
I lost 50 pounds.

829
01:06:09,537 --> 01:06:13,655
I feel good about myself
for the first time in my whole damn life

830
01:06:13,697 --> 01:06:17,849
and you're not gonna bring me down either,
so don't even try.

831
01:06:21,697 --> 01:06:23,494
Delicious.

832
01:06:25,457 --> 01:06:27,493
Good.

833
01:06:29,537 --> 01:06:32,335
And I am not trying to bring you down, little girl.

834
01:06:32,377 --> 01:06:37,167
It's a mother's duty to point out
when her child's acting dumber than usual.

835
01:06:37,217 --> 01:06:42,530
I mean,
trading in a perfectly good man like Miles

836
01:06:42,577 --> 01:06:46,172
for a strutting rooster like Walt Comeau

837
01:06:46,217 --> 01:06:48,447
simply defies imagination.

838
01:06:49,537 --> 01:06:53,212
Maybe one day I'll pack it all in like you,
but not today.

839
01:06:53,257 --> 01:06:56,294
People can change and I'm changing.

840
01:06:56,337 --> 01:07:00,125
You're not changing, Janine,
you're just losing weight.

841
01:07:00,737 --> 01:07:02,728
There's a difference.

842
01:07:02,777 --> 01:07:08,135
If you thought for two seconds about the effect
of all your foolishness on your daughter,

843
01:07:08,177 --> 01:07:10,372
that'd be a change.

844
01:07:13,417 --> 01:07:15,885
OK, John.

845
01:07:17,977 --> 01:07:19,968
Grab a seat.

846
01:07:22,057 --> 01:07:25,015
Christina, could I speak with you a minute?

847
01:07:29,977 --> 01:07:32,969
Christina, I need to ask you a favour.

848
01:07:34,457 --> 01:07:38,848
Recently there have been
some lunchroom incidents involving...and...

849
01:07:40,217 --> 01:07:45,086
Maybe if he could join you here in six,
since you take art together...

850
01:07:46,177 --> 01:07:51,012
There's a certain element in our school
that enjoys tormenting that...

851
01:07:51,777 --> 01:07:53,369
unhappy boy.

852
01:07:54,017 --> 01:07:57,134
His parents abandoned him
on his grandmother.

853
01:07:57,177 --> 01:07:59,975
He's missed an awful lot of school.

854
01:08:00,017 --> 01:08:03,976
What he needs is a friend.
I don't mean a girlfriend or anything.

855
01:08:04,017 --> 01:08:07,896
It would just be nice for him to know
that not everybody...

856
01:08:07,937 --> 01:08:09,529
Right.

857
01:08:23,857 --> 01:08:27,566
About time. Come on up.

858
01:08:27,617 --> 01:08:30,734
- That hasn't been scraped yet.
- So what?

859
01:08:30,777 --> 01:08:35,646
- What are you doing here, Dad?
- I'm painting! You owe me for two hours.

860
01:08:35,697 --> 01:08:39,406
- I don't owe you anything.
- What happened to your car seat?

861
01:08:39,457 --> 01:08:41,493
None of your business.

862
01:08:42,497 --> 01:08:45,091
Don't get mad at me. I didn't do it.

863
01:08:45,137 --> 01:08:47,048
I'm just an old man.

864
01:08:47,097 --> 01:08:49,486
- You have crumbs in your beard.
- So what?

865
01:08:53,577 --> 01:08:55,693
Peckerhead!

866
01:08:55,737 --> 01:08:59,047
- Tom?
- Where did this evil bastard come from?

867
01:08:59,097 --> 01:09:03,409
This is no evil bastard,
Tom, this is Miles Roby. You baptised him.

868
01:09:03,457 --> 01:09:06,927
- You married his parents...
- I know who it is!

869
01:09:06,977 --> 01:09:09,127
Look at him, he's a filthy degenerate.

870
01:09:09,177 --> 01:09:12,772
If he's filthy, it's from painting
our church for free, remember?

871
01:09:12,817 --> 01:09:17,607
He's a peckerhead and his mother was
a whore and don't think I didn't tell her either!

872
01:09:17,657 --> 01:09:20,649
Tom, Tom! Look at me, look at me.

873
01:09:21,457 --> 01:09:23,607
Remember what we talked about?

874
01:09:23,657 --> 01:09:28,777
I'm sorry you're not feeling well today
but this behaviour is intolerable.

875
01:09:28,817 --> 01:09:30,808
You owe Miles an apology.

876
01:09:36,297 --> 01:09:37,889
Forgive me.

877
01:09:41,897 --> 01:09:43,694
<i>Mom, are you all right?</i>

878
01:09:45,657 --> 01:09:48,376
- Should I get Father Tom?
- No.

879
01:09:57,737 --> 01:10:02,128
- I'm sorry, Miles.
- I doubt he even remembers my mother.

880
01:10:02,177 --> 01:10:06,489
It's ironic that Tom's condition may be
the only thing keeping us open for business.

881
01:10:06,537 --> 01:10:08,732
Look at my father.

882
01:10:08,777 --> 01:10:13,771
- So how come you're dreaming of eggs?
- I'm not dreaming of eggs.

883
01:10:15,337 --> 01:10:19,330
But the assignment was to draw
our most vivid dream.

884
01:10:28,137 --> 01:10:31,334
So how come you're thinking of eggs?

885
01:10:36,297 --> 01:10:40,495
It's something my mother once said to me
a long time ago.

886
01:10:42,697 --> 01:10:47,452
She said, "If chickens knew
what they were in for...

887
01:10:48,457 --> 01:10:50,448
"they'd stay in their eggs."

888
01:10:53,657 --> 01:10:55,852
She was frying eggs at the time.

889
01:11:06,537 --> 01:11:08,528
Is your mom dead?

890
01:11:11,497 --> 01:11:14,011
It's a possibility.

891
01:11:16,457 --> 01:11:21,451
Do we even want to know what those two
could possibly find to talk about?

892
01:11:22,897 --> 01:11:27,527
It's hard to imagine, all right.
A word to the wise.

893
01:11:27,577 --> 01:11:32,571
Don't let Max in unless you want to find your
valuables for sale at Empire Music and Pawn.

894
01:11:32,617 --> 01:11:37,293
- He'd steal from God?
- He's fearless, as far as God's concerned.

895
01:11:37,337 --> 01:11:42,286
I don't know if he's an atheist or he just thinks
he'll bullshit God like he does everybody else.

896
01:11:42,337 --> 01:11:44,805
Well, you give him this, anyway.

897
01:11:44,857 --> 01:11:47,246
Don't worry, it's not too much.

898
01:11:47,297 --> 01:11:50,334
Well, he'll be grateful. And it is too much.

899
01:11:50,377 --> 01:11:54,165
You know, actually, Father,
he won't be grateful.

900
01:11:54,217 --> 01:11:56,173
But he'll be glad to have it.

901
01:11:56,217 --> 01:12:01,416
Do you want my other half a sandwich?
Because I am full and I won't eat it.

902
01:12:10,217 --> 01:12:12,208
So this is your new boyfriend?

903
01:12:12,257 --> 01:12:16,375
- You're not supposed to be in here.
- I have a hall pass.

904
01:12:18,257 --> 01:12:20,452
Dickhead, get lost.

905
01:12:22,137 --> 01:12:26,130
My old girlfriend is gonna tell me
why she doesn't like me any more.

906
01:12:30,657 --> 01:12:35,651
Billy Wolf sprained his ankle at practice.
I'm gonna be starting against Fairhaven.

907
01:12:35,697 --> 01:12:39,531
- Congratulations.
- The coach was gonna start me anyway.

908
01:12:39,577 --> 01:12:43,172
Thank you, though.
You gonna come to the game?

909
01:12:44,657 --> 01:12:47,376
Everyone's going.
They're gonna hang out afterwards.

910
01:12:47,417 --> 01:12:50,534
Candace is coming. You should come.

911
01:12:50,577 --> 01:12:53,137
- Maybe.
- Maybe?

912
01:12:54,457 --> 01:12:56,288
Maybe?

913
01:13:00,337 --> 01:13:03,056
I've changed a lot since last spring.

914
01:13:03,937 --> 01:13:09,728
It just makes me really angry when you...
you won't even give me a second chance.

915
01:13:13,697 --> 01:13:18,088
I got an idea. Why don't we bring
your new boyfriend along with us?

916
01:13:18,137 --> 01:13:20,332
- No, leave him alone.
- Dickhead!

917
01:13:20,817 --> 01:13:23,285
- Don't.
- Dickhead.

918
01:13:23,337 --> 01:13:25,771
You! Turn around, look at me!

919
01:13:26,737 --> 01:13:29,570
Yeah, I'm talking to you.

920
01:13:29,617 --> 01:13:33,326
- What's your name?
- His name is John. John Voss.

921
01:13:34,937 --> 01:13:37,167
John Voss.

922
01:13:37,857 --> 01:13:42,851
No hard feelings there, John Voss.
You want to hang with us after the game?

923
01:13:42,897 --> 01:13:47,413
- OK.
- Did you hear that? It's OK with John Voss.

924
01:13:47,457 --> 01:13:50,210
If you leave him alone,
I'll go to the game, OK?

925
01:13:53,417 --> 01:13:58,445
Hey, dickhead. I mean, John Voss,
Tick's gonna come, too, all right?

926
01:14:01,617 --> 01:14:03,448
Cheap bastard!

927
01:14:05,937 --> 01:14:09,327
He's a sissy, you know, that young one.

928
01:14:10,217 --> 01:14:11,809
What?

929
01:14:12,777 --> 01:14:16,816
- You're just mad cos I got paid, you didn't.
- I'm thrilled that you got paid.

930
01:14:16,857 --> 01:14:21,647
Maybe you can make it to the end of the week
without hitting me up for a loan.

931
01:14:23,937 --> 01:14:27,407
- What are you doing?
- Glove box won't open.

932
01:14:27,457 --> 01:14:32,326
That's because it's locked.
People keep taking money out of it.

933
01:14:32,377 --> 01:14:35,414
That little lock wouldn't stop anybody.

934
01:14:43,697 --> 01:14:46,165
You're not gonna get this $20 bill.

935
01:14:47,937 --> 01:14:52,488
Boy, if I was you,
I'd start courting that cripple, Cindy Whiting.

936
01:14:53,417 --> 01:14:56,409
And you wonder
why I don't come to you for advice.

937
01:14:56,457 --> 01:15:00,973
If all I had to do to get my hands on $10 million
was to marry a cripple...

938
01:15:02,417 --> 01:15:05,215
- would I ever!
- Yeah, then you'd leave her.

939
01:15:06,417 --> 01:15:08,009
God.

940
01:15:09,937 --> 01:15:12,371
Give me a screwdriver,
I could fix that for you.

941
01:15:13,577 --> 01:15:16,774
If you'd marry that cripple,
you'd own the whole town.

942
01:15:16,817 --> 01:15:22,210
Tick could go to a good college
and there might just be enough left over

943
01:15:22,257 --> 01:15:24,452
so I could spend the winter in the Keys.

944
01:15:24,497 --> 01:15:27,091
- Could you not refer to her that way?
- What way?

945
01:15:27,137 --> 01:15:30,527
- As a cripple. Could you not do that?
- What way should I call her?

946
01:15:30,577 --> 01:15:34,172
Don't call her anything,
don't refer to her at all. How'd that be?

947
01:15:34,217 --> 01:15:37,687
A fellow down in the Keys
called himself a cripple all the time.

948
01:15:37,737 --> 01:15:40,934
- He said, "Max, don't ever be a cripple."
- Good God!

949
01:15:40,977 --> 01:15:44,413
- Well, don't get mad at me is all I'm saying.
- Give me a...

950
01:15:44,457 --> 01:15:50,248
It wasn't me that run over her. If your mother
had told you to marry her, you'd marry her.

951
01:15:50,297 --> 01:15:52,333
We'd have 10 million bucks to split.

952
01:15:52,377 --> 01:15:55,972
If Mom was still alive,
she and I would have 10 million bucks.

953
01:15:56,017 --> 01:15:58,736
You would be shit out of luck, partner.

954
01:15:59,537 --> 01:16:02,927
Get along home, little Cindy

955
01:16:08,817 --> 01:16:12,571
- All right, all right, all right!
- I'll marry you one day

956
01:16:13,137 --> 01:16:17,733
Good Lord, that's quite a crowd.
Looks like you could use some help.

957
01:16:18,937 --> 01:16:21,531
I'm available if the money is right.

958
01:16:22,817 --> 01:16:25,615
- The cavalry has arrived!
- How you doing?

959
01:16:25,657 --> 01:16:28,854
Not bad for a one-armed man.
Charlene needs help.

960
01:16:28,897 --> 01:16:32,606
- Dad, put this on before you go out front.
- And wash your hands.

961
01:16:33,137 --> 01:16:37,176
- Wash my hands so I can bus dirty dishes?
- Just wash them.

962
01:16:37,217 --> 01:16:39,367
Hi.

963
01:16:39,417 --> 01:16:41,408
Hey, who's this? Who are you?

964
01:16:41,457 --> 01:16:43,652
This is John from my art class.

965
01:16:43,697 --> 01:16:47,053
Uncle David said we needed a new busboy.
I showed him how.

966
01:16:47,097 --> 01:16:51,056
Take a look at Brian.
He's a walking appetite suppressant.

967
01:16:52,217 --> 01:16:54,811
Brian. Come here for a minute.

968
01:16:54,857 --> 01:16:57,974
- What?
- You gotta go home.

969
01:16:58,017 --> 01:17:01,373
What do you mean? I can't help it.
Something bit me. I can still work.

970
01:17:01,417 --> 01:17:04,409
Yeah, but people eat here, Brian. Go home.

971
01:17:04,457 --> 01:17:06,925
Hello, John. Miles.

972
01:17:12,257 --> 01:17:15,055
- Hi, Grandpa!
- Tickeroo!

973
01:17:15,097 --> 01:17:17,327
Hi.

974
01:17:17,377 --> 01:17:19,937
Your beard is scratchy, Grandpa.

975
01:17:20,457 --> 01:17:23,608
- And you smell.
- Well, so do you.

976
01:17:23,657 --> 01:17:26,808
Difference is you're young so you smell good.

977
01:17:26,857 --> 01:17:28,848
Here, just bus the dishes, Dad.

978
01:17:28,897 --> 01:17:32,287
You take any of Charlene's tips,
she'll gut you like a carp.

979
01:17:32,337 --> 01:17:35,727
Down in the Keys,
the waitresses split their tips with the busboys.

980
01:17:35,777 --> 01:17:38,769
Why don't you give that a try,
let me know how it turns out?

981
01:17:38,817 --> 01:17:42,207
Old man, you steal one dime of mine,
I will castrate you.

982
01:17:42,257 --> 01:17:44,532
- I've already warned him.
- Castrate you.

983
01:17:51,017 --> 01:17:53,485
- Hey, Walt.
- Business is really picking up?

984
01:17:53,537 --> 01:17:54,936
It's great.

985
01:17:54,977 --> 01:17:58,174
- This upscale idea of yours is really good.
- Yeah, it is.

986
01:17:58,217 --> 01:18:02,529
I'm in the john and I'm thinking, "How can he
put even more money into the box,

987
01:18:02,577 --> 01:18:04,568
"you know, add even more class?"

988
01:18:04,617 --> 01:18:08,405
- What did you come up with?
- You add an E on the end of "Grill".

989
01:18:10,257 --> 01:18:13,055
G-R-I-L-L-E.

990
01:18:13,097 --> 01:18:16,089
- Now, that is a great idea, Walt.
- Thanks.

991
01:18:25,377 --> 01:18:29,495
Why don't you just clean those two tables,
then you can join your friends.

992
01:18:29,537 --> 01:18:32,370
- Is that Candace out there?
- Yeah.

993
01:18:33,417 --> 01:18:37,410
I thought you gave Zack Minty
his walking papers last spring.

994
01:18:37,457 --> 01:18:40,051
What's that mean?

995
01:18:40,097 --> 01:18:45,091
- I just know how much you hate him.
- I don't hate him. He's just a boy.

996
01:18:45,137 --> 01:18:48,129
What I do hate
is you being afraid to tell me things.

997
01:18:48,177 --> 01:18:50,566
That's cos there's nothing to tell, OK?

998
01:18:50,617 --> 01:18:54,405
We're going out as a group.
It's not just me and Zack.

999
01:18:55,217 --> 01:18:58,971
Hey, John, can you give us a minute,
please?

1000
01:18:59,017 --> 01:19:00,609
Thanks.

1001
01:19:02,057 --> 01:19:05,254
What about Donny, the boy from the Vineyard?
I thought you two...

1002
01:19:05,297 --> 01:19:07,288
I haven't even gotten a letter.

1003
01:19:07,337 --> 01:19:11,046
It hasn't been that long and
be fair, you haven't written him either.

1004
01:19:11,097 --> 01:19:13,292
Well, we still don't have e-mail.

1005
01:19:16,697 --> 01:19:19,973
- Do you want me to let John off, too?
- No.

1006
01:19:26,937 --> 01:19:27,926
Where have you been?

1007
01:19:27,977 --> 01:19:30,172
Talking to Audrey,
the manager at The Lamplighter.

1008
01:19:30,217 --> 01:19:34,210
She said they were slow all evening.
So was The Eating House out on 92.

1009
01:19:34,257 --> 01:19:38,853
The only restaurant in Dexter County
that did any volume tonight was us.

1010
01:19:38,897 --> 01:19:40,888
I made great tips, too.

1011
01:19:40,937 --> 01:19:44,532
Selling fajitas to Mainers.
Who'd have thought you could make a living?

1012
01:19:44,577 --> 01:19:48,616
The Lamplighter may have done shit
but they still out-grossed us.

1013
01:19:48,657 --> 01:19:50,807
Because they sell booze.

1014
01:19:51,897 --> 01:19:53,376
Yeah.

1015
01:19:54,337 --> 01:20:00,128
Sure, we did good tonight. We'll never do
any better. We can't put any more tables in.

1016
01:20:00,177 --> 01:20:03,886
We can't put any more people
at the tables we already got.

1017
01:20:03,937 --> 01:20:08,215
- We killed ourselves tonight. For what?
- I know, I know.

1018
01:20:08,257 --> 01:20:10,976
Don't just say, "I know, I know," Miles.

1019
01:20:11,017 --> 01:20:14,612
What do you what from me, David?
I talked to Mrs Whiting.

1020
01:20:14,657 --> 01:20:19,094
- I showed her the books.
- No, I don't want to hear about Mrs Whiting!

1021
01:20:19,137 --> 01:20:24,336
Jesus Christ,
what a good Catholic boy you are, Miles!

1022
01:20:25,977 --> 01:20:30,767
Somebody tells you you can't have something,
you just genuflect and accept it.

1023
01:20:30,817 --> 01:20:33,854
Look at yourself, look! Have you seen this?

1024
01:20:33,897 --> 01:20:39,529
Every time you come back from that woman's
house, you've got scratch marks on you.

1025
01:20:39,577 --> 01:20:43,365
- Have you thought about what that means?
- She's got a psychotic cat.

1026
01:20:43,417 --> 01:20:46,727
No, it means she's toying with you, Miles.

1027
01:20:47,737 --> 01:20:53,448
She owns the whole town, yeah, yeah,
but she only owns you because you let her.

1028
01:21:06,137 --> 01:21:09,607
- $500,000.
- What?

1029
01:21:09,657 --> 01:21:13,855
What the bookstore on the Vineyard costs,
the one you want me to buy.

1030
01:21:13,897 --> 01:21:17,606
- Where will I come up with $500,000?
- Screw that, I'm talking about you.

1031
01:21:17,657 --> 01:21:21,047
Every time that you want something,
really want it,

1032
01:21:21,097 --> 01:21:24,885
you shove it away in some dark corner
so you don't have to think about it.

1033
01:21:24,937 --> 01:21:28,009
As if you're gonna be punished for wanting it.

1034
01:21:28,697 --> 01:21:31,734
Jesus, it breaks my heart!

1035
01:21:32,577 --> 01:21:36,013
And we both know where you got that from
and it's not Dad.

1036
01:21:36,057 --> 01:21:38,525
You know what, Charlene?
This needs to be said.

1037
01:21:38,577 --> 01:21:43,412
Tell that woman to get us a liquor licence
or go fuck herself!

1038
01:21:43,457 --> 01:21:46,927
And if you don't wanna do it for yourself,
do it for Tick

1039
01:21:46,977 --> 01:21:51,289
because she's soaking up more
of your defeatism and passivity every day.

1040
01:21:51,337 --> 01:21:53,726
David, look at your brother.

1041
01:21:53,777 --> 01:21:58,692
Just be quiet for a minute and look at him.

1042
01:22:02,297 --> 01:22:04,094
Aw, shit.

1043
01:22:05,697 --> 01:22:07,892
OK, I'm going home.

1044
01:22:12,857 --> 01:22:15,849
Sorry. I spoiled the party.

1045
01:22:15,897 --> 01:22:18,365
- David, you don't have to go.
- No, I do.

1046
01:22:18,417 --> 01:22:21,568
It's time I got home
and tended to my pot empire.

1047
01:22:22,977 --> 01:22:25,172
That was a joke, Miles.

1048
01:22:25,217 --> 01:22:28,812
I've got one plant in the basement, Miles,
under a heat lamp.

1049
01:22:28,857 --> 01:22:31,451
- Whatever.
- Whatever's right.

1050
01:22:34,097 --> 01:22:37,089
I'd better go. I'll be right back.

1051
01:22:46,177 --> 01:22:48,168
- Miles.
- Hey, Bill.

1052
01:23:02,937 --> 01:23:06,566
Hey, he does care about you, you know.

1053
01:23:07,857 --> 01:23:10,451
He just thinks you eat too much shit.

1054
01:23:12,057 --> 01:23:14,048
I take it you agree.

1055
01:23:14,897 --> 01:23:16,694
I don't know, Miles.

1056
01:23:16,737 --> 01:23:20,855
You've got to be the most cautious man
I've ever run across.

1057
01:23:20,897 --> 01:23:22,489
Yeah.

1058
01:23:22,537 --> 01:23:26,928
You know how when Max wants something,
how he's always got a plan?

1059
01:23:26,977 --> 01:23:30,367
No matter how hard you try,
you can't distract him.

1060
01:23:30,737 --> 01:23:34,127
David thinks you get distracted
by other people.

1061
01:23:46,417 --> 01:23:50,046
Yeah, well,
he doesn't even know the worst of it.

1062
01:23:50,617 --> 01:23:54,087
I invited Cindy Whiting
to homecoming tomorrow.

1063
01:23:54,137 --> 01:23:56,856
That's really sweet, Miles.

1064
01:23:56,897 --> 01:24:01,846
That woman could use a little joy in her life.
That is a really nice thing that you've done.

1065
01:24:01,897 --> 01:24:05,685
It was Cindy who nursed my mother
through the cancer right to the end.

1066
01:24:05,737 --> 01:24:09,571
Mrs Whiting took her in
but it was Cindy who took care of her.

1067
01:24:10,977 --> 01:24:14,765
I left school to be close by
but the truth is I never got out there much.

1068
01:24:14,817 --> 01:24:17,775
My mother was furious with me for quitting.

1069
01:24:19,137 --> 01:24:21,128
I didn't know that.

1070
01:24:26,017 --> 01:24:31,614
Why do you think I crossed that river
every day for the last ten years?

1071
01:24:31,657 --> 01:24:36,685
So you could end up working
at the Empire Grill? Don't do this, Miles.

1072
01:24:36,737 --> 01:24:39,774
You go back to school, you graduate.

1073
01:24:39,817 --> 01:24:45,175
I'm going to graduate, Mom.
Just not this semester.

1074
01:24:45,217 --> 01:24:47,526
- For now, this is where I belong.
- No.

1075
01:24:47,577 --> 01:24:52,014
- As soon as you're better, I'll go back.
- I'm not going to get better. Don't pretend.

1076
01:24:52,057 --> 01:24:54,446
- Mom, look...
- No. Miles...

1077
01:24:54,497 --> 01:24:57,455
Mom, Mrs Whiting's making me a manager.

1078
01:24:57,497 --> 01:24:59,886
- Later...
- But you'll end up trapped here.

1079
01:24:59,937 --> 01:25:04,852
Can't you see, Miles?
She knows how much you love me.

1080
01:25:07,097 --> 01:25:09,486
Don't be kept from your life.

1081
01:25:11,297 --> 01:25:15,256
- Don't, for me. Not for me.
- Mom...

1082
01:25:20,857 --> 01:25:23,052
I guess you heard most of that.

1083
01:25:24,777 --> 01:25:26,210
Miles...

1084
01:25:27,297 --> 01:25:29,333
it's not your fault.

1085
01:25:30,097 --> 01:25:32,895
Thank you for taking care of her.
You have been so...

1086
01:25:32,937 --> 01:25:35,531
Don't be silly, Miles.

1087
01:25:35,577 --> 01:25:40,571
She's been a mother to me.
All those years she cared for me.

1088
01:25:44,737 --> 01:25:46,728
My only mother, really.

1089
01:25:48,697 --> 01:25:51,291
I'll go in. I can usually calm her down.

1090
01:25:55,457 --> 01:25:59,848
I went over there one night, near the end.

1091
01:26:02,497 --> 01:26:05,216
Cindy was coming out of my mother's room.

1092
01:26:07,097 --> 01:26:09,816
I don't know how we got started, but...

1093
01:26:10,937 --> 01:26:13,929
At first, it was just her kissing me...

1094
01:26:15,057 --> 01:26:17,048
and then I was kissing her, too.

1095
01:26:18,257 --> 01:26:22,853
And then we were, you know,
grappling, groping.

1096
01:26:25,617 --> 01:26:29,451
We were half-undressed
and then my mother cried out.

1097
01:26:30,737 --> 01:26:33,456
And Cindy put herself together
and went back in.

1098
01:26:33,497 --> 01:26:37,092
I was supposed to stay there and wait for her,

1099
01:26:37,137 --> 01:26:42,165
but by the time she got my mother
settled again, I realised what I was doing

1100
01:26:42,217 --> 01:26:45,812
and I just got out of there.

1101
01:26:45,857 --> 01:26:47,449
I bolted.

1102
01:26:50,897 --> 01:26:54,936
For the longest time, I've imagined...

1103
01:26:54,977 --> 01:26:59,573
what her face must have looked like
when she discovered I was gone.

1104
01:27:06,617 --> 01:27:09,006
There's no need to repeat that story.

1105
01:27:13,897 --> 01:27:17,094
Get rid of a hangover. That's pretty good.

1106
01:27:26,977 --> 01:27:28,968
David's right about one thing.

1107
01:27:30,697 --> 01:27:33,495
I don't really go after what I want, do I?

1108
01:27:35,297 --> 01:27:37,208
Miles.

1109
01:27:37,257 --> 01:27:41,728
It's not like I don't know
you've had this crush on me, like, forever.

1110
01:27:43,777 --> 01:27:45,768
You know how fond I am of you.

1111
01:27:47,337 --> 01:27:49,646
You're about the sweetest man I know.

1112
01:27:51,257 --> 01:27:53,566
- Do you wanna know what?
- What?

1113
01:27:55,257 --> 01:27:59,614
I'd like to take you home
and make love with you.

1114
01:28:02,577 --> 01:28:04,169
Except I...

1115
01:28:05,177 --> 01:28:08,328
I couldn't stand how disappointed you'd be.

1116
01:28:08,377 --> 01:28:13,371
And you wouldn't be able to conceal it either.
Not with that face of yours.

1117
01:28:13,417 --> 01:28:17,888
Well, the next time you feel the impulse,
let me know.

1118
01:28:18,937 --> 01:28:21,405
I just might want to risk it.

1119
01:28:29,337 --> 01:28:32,135
Hey, listen...

1120
01:28:32,177 --> 01:28:35,089
You did a good deed, hiring that Voss boy.

1121
01:28:35,137 --> 01:28:37,935
You know what they say. No good deed goes...

1122
01:28:37,977 --> 01:28:40,013
Unpunished.

1123
01:28:40,057 --> 01:28:44,653
He's had it pretty rough. His parents
were low-rent drug dealers in Portland.

1124
01:28:44,697 --> 01:28:47,495
When he was little,
they'd stuff him in a laundry bag

1125
01:28:47,537 --> 01:28:52,133
and hang him on the inside of a closet door
while they conducted business.

1126
01:28:52,177 --> 01:28:55,567
They didn't always come back for him
right away.

1127
01:28:55,617 --> 01:28:58,927
- Good night, Bea.
- So long.

1128
01:28:58,977 --> 01:29:02,049
That's awful. Did you hear that?

1129
01:29:05,057 --> 01:29:08,652
My dear brother has this notion
that you and I should go into business.

1130
01:29:08,697 --> 01:29:11,894
Well, I've heard dumber ideas.

1131
01:29:12,897 --> 01:29:15,286
It'dhave to be your call, Miles.

1132
01:29:18,777 --> 01:29:24,135
- I'm not quite sure I see how to make it work.
- Let me know if you change your mind.

1133
01:29:24,177 --> 01:29:27,487
You married my daughter so I owe you one.

1134
01:30:07,257 --> 01:30:09,976
I'm gonna hit the shower.

1135
01:30:10,017 --> 01:30:13,373
Oh, yeah? Well, I have a better idea.

1136
01:30:16,097 --> 01:30:17,689
Oh, God!

1137
01:30:17,737 --> 01:30:21,127
Oh, God! Oh, God!

1138
01:30:21,177 --> 01:30:23,133
Oh, God!

1139
01:30:23,177 --> 01:30:28,046
Oh, God! Miles never would have
found that spot. Oh, God!

1140
01:30:38,737 --> 01:30:41,729
- Have a good day, now.
- Thanks. You, too.

1141
01:30:49,777 --> 01:30:52,086
Empire Grill.

1142
01:30:52,137 --> 01:30:54,128
Father Mark, hi.

1143
01:30:54,937 --> 01:30:56,734
Right now?

1144
01:30:56,777 --> 01:30:58,972
I'm running late, actually.

1145
01:30:59,017 --> 01:31:02,168
I can't figure out how he got it open.

1146
01:31:02,217 --> 01:31:06,608
He was always asking me for the combination
and getting mad when I wouldn't give it to him.

